when you call relation with `()` it returns you query builder instance not eloquent model collection and when you call it without `()` it will returns you collection and then by collections `map` you can call forceDelete Method on all one by one.

Eloquent events only works when you retrieve the models and then call methods.

like `User::where(&#39;id&#39;,1)-&gt;delete();` will not trigger `deleting` and `deleted` as you never get the model from database so no event binds its just equivalent to `\DB::table(&#39;users&#39;)-&gt;where(&#39;id&#39;,1)-&gt;delete();`

But when you call `User::where(&#39;id&#39;,1)-&gt;first()-&gt;delete();` Or `User::find(1)-&gt;delete();` now eloquent events of `deleting` and `deleted` will triggered as you create their models first by getting data from DB then whatever events binds to this Model are registered and when you call delete it will trigger its events.

